  "prompt": "Why do converts to Islam say that they have reverted to Islam?",
  "response": "When converts to Islam say they have \"reverted\" to Islam, they are often expressing a theological perspective that is rooted in Islamic belief. According to Islamic teachings, every human being is born in a state of *fitrah*, which is an innate predisposition toward recognizing and worshipping the one true God (Allah). This concept is derived from the Quran and Hadith (sayings and actions of the Prophet Muhammad).\n\nThe idea is that all people are naturally inclined toward monotheism and submission to God, but their environment, upbringing, or choices may lead them away from this natural state. When someone says they have \"reverted\" to Islam, they are emphasizing that they are returning to their original, pure state of *fitrah* and embracing the belief and practice of Islam that they believe is inherent to human nature.\n\nIn contrast, the term \"convert\" implies a change from one belief system to another. For many Muslims, the word \"revert\" is preferred because it reflects the belief that they are not adopting something entirely new but are instead rediscovering and realigning with their true nature and purpose as created by God.\n\nThis perspective is deeply meaningful to many new Muslims, as it underscores the idea that their journey to Islam is a return to their spiritual roots rather than a radical departure from their past.",
